Chapter 1
The word "Cohren" is a proper noun and does not require translation. It could be a name of a place or a person. Without additional context, it remains "Cohren" in English. If you have more context or if you meant a full sentence, please provide that so I can assist you better.
0430 Italian Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He especially loathed it because he was responsible for rousing everyone else in his company. Silently, he got out of his bunk, put on his combat uniform, threw on his protective vest, and retrieved his belongings from the locker, being careful around a particular small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook attached to his belt. Everything he needed dangled from this hook, such as his breathing apparatus or his special goggles. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, the mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He pulled a lighter from one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit them and took a short drag before opening the door slightly. Last week, he had had to come up with quite a bit to wake the men and women under his supervision. He no longer used the alarm clock setting, as it usually didn't work and only produced a faint hiss from the speakers.
" wake her up?" Cohren turned around and saw Zugführer Nemic approaching him.
""Yes," Cohren replied.
"What do you want to try this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came towards him already dressed in full gear.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"From what did you wake up?" asked Cohren.
"First of all, we didn't feel like waiting for what you came up with today. And secondly, the shock troops that rise earliest should get to choose the morning ration," replied one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, Sergeant," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. In the barracks, a loud, shrill alarm sounded. Inside, he heard softly muttered curses and people running around in a panic.
"Man, Valturi," said Nemic. "One would think they would have learned to wake up at the same time as you."
"Well, my people from the training camp learned it," Cohren replied, pointing at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the platoon and squad leaders also know that they must rise before their units."
Seconds later, the rest of the company emerged. They had everything they needed, from personal belongings to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, while others seemed irritated.
"Good morning," said Cohren cheerfully.
"With all due respect, Sir, why do you have to wake us up so early?" asked a Stormtrooper sergeant.
"Because the regular alarms suck and because Daybreak won't oversleep," said Cohren.
"Cook all your personal belongings," Cohren continued. As a lieutenant and the executive officer of the company, he was responsible for overseeing and supporting them along with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We will not be returning here. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack your rations."
The members of the Exodus Company quickly dispersed. They were part of the second assault division, second army. Before they were consolidated, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company had been split, and this was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to Lieutenant Colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked side by side in the glow of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward operating base. Most of them had red-tinted glass to avoid detection by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to wild-weasel attacks from both the air and the ground to counter them.
"A new day and a new task for the hellhounds," said Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advanced forward base outside Iano. We will support the ground attack," Cohren replied and took a drag on his cigarette. He attributed part of his smoking habit to Craith, but a year in the field changed a person, so he said nothing.
"Fucking hell. Things are getting worse at the front," murmured Nemic. "All the news reads: 'Support war efforts. Send aid to the Kurgan front.' What about some help for the Howland front?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren and flicked the ashes of his cigarette into the mud. "At least we're starting with the first armed train and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be there."
"Shaw has clarified a ride-sharing opportunity for us?" Nemic asked a bit surprised.
"Yes. He is, in fact, not as bad as I thought. While he's not particularly friendly, you can get along with him."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and at the same time put his backpack on. "All units of the Exodus Company will meet at the West Fleet Parking when they're ready. We'll depart with the first armed convoy at 0500."
At a rapid pace, he received responses from the squad leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking sergeants when they all arrived here. The four of them had become close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren felt as if he had known them forever, although it had only been two years. They were squad leaders, but Craith had taken over command of the second platoon a week ago, as the previous leader was medically discharged after being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
On their way to the vehicle fleet, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four infantry fighting vehicles. The crew members were walking around, ensuring that their machines were ready for action. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the commander of the armed column. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came toward them, as usual with an expressionless face.
"Leutnant Nemic... Leutnant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was moving slower, while looking at Cohren's pistol holster and then looking up again. "I assume the company is ready?"
